>>61046762
Nerd culture in the US is contrarian. In the 1990s, we were constantly being told that everyone was really happy about everything and everything was better than it had ever been before in every way. Not everyone agreed with these blanket statements (*cough* Waco *cough*) but this happy clappy bullshit was The Narrative then. So nerds sought out escapist fantasies of over-the-top grimdark. Pen-and-paper RPGs about werewolves and vampires and the end of the world were big with nerds then. Neon Genesis Evangelion was the New Hotness with its psychological horror, antihero protagonist, and morally dubious characters.

Since 9/11 the normies have been in this really depressed mood and a lot of them seem to be starting to think that everything really IS going to shit. Nerd culture since then embraces Chinese cartoons about moeblob slice-of-life stuff and high-adventure high-fantasy MMORPGs.

Nerd culture in the 90s was really interested in vampires. Go read about all the pen-and-paper horror/vampire/zombie RPGs that were yuge with nerds 25 years ago. Now it's the normies who are obsessed with zombies and vampires, and nerds won't touch that shit.

As an aside, when zombies and the zombie apocalypse are humongous in popculture, when the normies are obsessed with vampires, it means something. In the 1970s the normies were obsessed with this stuff. It resonated with them. It struck a chord with them because there was this pervasive sense that everything was falling apart, that the government was corrupt and inept, that the institutions were failing, that society was collapsing. Zombie unthinkingly destroy everything. They are entropy personified, and throwing out all the rules and killing them with insane ultraviolence is A-OK. Vampires are eternally beautiful and superhuman and not bound by your mortal rules. When the normies get this stuff stuck in their heads, it means they're terrified of the future.

I just thought I'd share that. Here's a cow.
